No, that's good.

Go to Europe for two years, three years, spend more time in labor camps, slave labor.
Okay, then I'll come back the next life, got another one, I'll do something different.
You know, you only have one and...
I was already told what to do long enough, much too long.
I had started out pretty good as a student and then at work it was just terrible.
It took me four years to survive.
And, of course, in the early parts, remember, there was no Europe to speak of.
It was just devastating.
Because, you know, the Soviet zone was probably out after about 1952 or 1953.
By that time, you were in such bad terms with the Russians.
Yeah, but I didn't read the paper that much.
And politics, I had it up to here.
Right.
So you stayed away from the paper, and you stayed away from...
I read it, but it didn't really, you know, I...
I wasn't...
I wasn't going to let anybody make a decision over my life when I had taken my life into my hands already.
And why should I give it back to some clown and tell me we have now a directive and I can't help it, I'm only a little bureaucrat, it comes from above,
You must do this, that, and the other.
Forget it.
Do your thing.
I do mine.
I just never could see it.
I know it doesn't sound very law-abiding.
It's kind of outside the law.
But there has to be a higher law that you can live your own life and not have to be sent all over the world.
Were you that bothered in the same way when you were drafted and they were saying, now this is what you're going to have to do?
Was it the same sense of, don't tell me what to do, or was it weaker back then?

Well, I have to admit in those days, you know, we do have a lot of, we're into the military, the Germans are, and being from part of Prussia, you know, they have a lot of military traditions, so I have to admit, you know, okay, I do my stuff.
And in those days, they were doing

this kind of blitz thing they were going in and no more battles this is it we're just going to do this and that and the other and people were coming from Hungary I met some real nice girls from Budapest came to tennis tournaments you know I mean it was a whole new world was opening up people from Poland would come in so it was a kind of a different Europe say

Well, did the attitude that it was okay then last through the period that you were still officially free, you know, even up through the classical, or was there a point that you became annoyed with having them tell you, now you go here, now you go there, now you retreat?
Absolutely.
Absolutely.
It probably, it just built up, you know, from the time, of course, the war, the actual battle experience started it, you know, because that's, that's,
you know, sleeping in a foxhole, digging in a foxhole every other night.
I mean, that's just enough to drive you crazy.
And then we were taken prisoner.
We just went from one camp to another in North Africa, and that went on for months and months and months.
And in this country, we transferred them months and months, and, you know, just constantly being moved.
I'd rather move on my own and not have anybody tell me where to go.
I have to move or stay or starve.
If I want to starve, I can starve.
It was interesting what you just said.
Since you said you've got hives, every time she said it, it's time to move.
Yeah.
So it wasn't that it was your choice then.
I think that's probably quite accurate.
The actual moving doesn't bother me.
It's probably when I'm ready to move.
But she was ready to move, so...
So you didn't get the hives when you hopped the train back to the Texas border to try and go across or anything like that?
So some of it probably is pretty hard to understand from a law-abiding, citizen viewpoint, you know?
I hear that all the time.
I get that message.
I even got it from my nieces.
Why didn't you, you know?

it's except my dear wife never pushes me on that particular point that that is that freedom believe it or not as I have more freedom as a fugitive than I probably ever will have in my life I have no number nobody can reach me you know if I as long as I pay now I have of course a number I pay into it now they're getting everything already crisscrossed with computers yes and I you know but in
In those early days, I was totally free.
I was still, I could have been drafted to the Korean War.
I didn't have to go to the Korean War, and so on.
It's just an incredible... How did you, could you have been drafted?
Did you get a sort of selective service card or something?
Or had you become a citizen at that point?
I could have.
I'm not following it.
Had you become a citizen of the United States?
Had you not been a fugitive citizen?
Yeah, yeah.
Yeah, I could have been probably drafted.
I was only in my, what, 30s, maybe.
Yeah, you could have.
I was in the borderline, her brother.
Did you ever consider getting citizenship?
Yeah, I would like to.
There was a way, you know, a way without having to go through the, as I understand it, you know, the,
The jail and the deportation and all that kind of stuff.
That's not going to happen.
Nobody's moving anywhere until it's pinned down.

Hopes were really high for a while there when they started about general pardon for these illegal aliens, but it's all stopped again, you know, so that you wouldn't have to go through this and just, you know, come out of that.
That I would do, you see.
If some emperor would say, OK, I'm going to pardon these people and we start fresh and get this paperwork done, I don't remember how.
Wouldn't it be nice when you get a letter from the Attorney General's office in Washington saying that...
I'm pardoned.
...Georg Gettner, a.k.a.
Peter Peterson, a.k.a.
Dennis Wiles, no outstanding wants, warrants, no charges.
All charges have been dropped.
may apply for citizenship at any opportunity.
Signed, Edwin Meese, Attorney General.
I don't think it's that far off.
No, I don't think it's that far off.
Well, it's the fats and the fire, so... Oh, I don't think that there's...
But it's not up to me anymore, so...
Well, it still is.
It still is up to you.
It's still up to you until the moment you decide to do whatever you want to do.
Because you can say...
I can do it.
I want to do it.
It's just...
Because you always know that you can change your name and disappear in a matter of moments.
Nobody will ever hear from you.
And you could go any place and be anybody again.
I think, Arnie, I think those days will pass too.
I think that's behind me, I'm afraid.
It's like my skiing days are behind me.
It's not afraid at all.
I think it's a very healthy sign.
It's like the caterpillar that sheds its skin and comes out a butterfly.
I think it's a very real... That's a nice way to describe it.
Yeah, I think so.
I think it's...
I did shed my skin, and I go, that's very good.
Yeah, and the butterfly that's underneath comes out.
Yeah, that's true.
It's not something that... A child, you can push and nag and hit, but it's not going to walk until all the skills are in place, and it stands up and takes a few steps.
And I think it's the same thing with changes like this.

like with changing from peter peterson to dennis wilds there's a point in which it is necessary to shed the skin the snake skin and move to the next stage and i think this is exactly you must be comfortable growing comfortable with it yeah otherwise you wouldn't yeah be willing to shed your skin for the next stage because you know that nothing's going to happen first you can always disappear and you can always just uh become
George Glotz and disappear.
That's the enemy.
There's no...
I don't see any difficulty at all in any case.
You're not making a move until everything is pinned down.
I don't... You're not put in jeopardy at all?
You know, it's...
I've got a post office box number, and you can disappear at any time.
So don't feel that you're on a train that's got no way to get off.
But I think it's nice to stay on.
Well, now that I've found my family in Germany, things have changed in that respect.
I didn't think I had any left.
And Jane is very supportive in everything.
I'll bet people will contact you for psychological studies of fugitive years.
Agencies may come to you to find out how to tighten up their procedures to keep illegal aliens out.
I have a feeling that you're... Because you have an experience that nobody else has.
You're the longest running FBI fugitive.
And they told that to me with a little awe.
It was Bill Tribble who was there.
Do you know, he said, that your man is the longest future on the FBI list?
We've never had anybody that's been out for 38 years.
No, they haven't.
he would love you to call he would love you to call

He will be the first one I call.

Not because they have any plans.
They don't.

The best way to befriend the authorities is to make sure that they know

And that everybody has to, we have to get the ducks in the right line before we shoot.
Get all the ducks in a row.
Oh, yes.
Oh, sure.
Everybody has to move at the same time.
And then all it's going to be is, that's the protection.
is that everything, there can't be any slippage, behind the scenes injustices or anything like that.

Letters from the Jewish Defense League?
Could be anything.

Like I say, I have nothing but good feelings toward my friend Herb Lipkin who taught me everything about
business and made business an interesting thing, which is more than anybody else could have done.

I've loved it ever since.

Bill Klein, yeah, and they were strictly skiing and all I had to do was be a good skier and a good instructor and that he didn't get any complaints from the students and stay away from these rich girls.
You asked me to remind you to tell the story about Peddler Hill.
I didn't tell the Peddler Hill story.
Oh, Peddler Hill.
I'd forgotten that little
place that when I was, I thought I did, I think we may have that on the tape.
Tell me two or three things about it.
I was looking for a place where I could have my own ski school.
And I found that place called Peddler Hill in the Gold Country in the National Forest.
And with a couple of rope tours.
And the owner of this place, and I can't think of his name right now, but he was a very
little short guy, very feisty, cute little fellow, gray hair.
Well, he wasn't that old in those days, probably, but he was older than I was.
And a very lively fellow.
And he says, sure, we need a guy here.
You can get your sign up there and open your ski school.
And he just finished a little lodge, and just dormitories, women and men, and a bar.
Was it Sonora that was wide open gambling?
You had to go through Pedley Hill.
Is that Sonora?
Yeah, Sonora.
Yeah, Silver Lake is about it.
It's a Kit Carson Pass.
It's one of the passes that goes over.
Kit Carson Pass.
And Sonora, a really old town, they were gambling in red light districts when I was there.
Excellent food, wide open town.
We had to go through Sonora to get to that.
Jackson?
Was it Jackson, not Sonora?
Jackson.
Jackson was a town, a wide open town.
And the Filipino and the farm laborers would come and support the gambling and the rest of it.
And so one day, on a Sunday afternoon, I had one student.
Everybody was going, driving home.
It was very close to Oakland.
This gal student I had was a doctor, psychiatrist, a young lady, probably in her late 20s, early 30s.
And she said, all of a sudden, out of the clear blue sky, she says, Dennis, I want you to stay with me because Mr. so-and-so, I can't think of his name, has been making passes at me.
She's been there all week.
She was going to stay another week.
And I was kind of leery of that.
That's kind of a strange thing.
I can't believe that.
He's married.
He's got his wife there.
He's got his daughter there.
He's got his daughter has a trial.
She's divorced, all right, but she has a boyfriend there.
So he's got a lot of family.
He wouldn't go around making passes.
Well, I said, OK.
I said, OK, well, let's go into the bar and have some drinks and go into the bar.
You could see 90 miles to Yosemite.
And
I guess we had some dinner, went back to the bar, and he kind of came around a couple of times wanting to know how things were.
And she kept saying, you know, you've got to stay with me tonight.
It's been coming and passing.
So good old Dennis said, OK.
So I sneaked into the women's dorm.
About what year was this?
And we waited in the dark.
We waited and waited and just whispered and talked.

In the lower box, right.

Today.

I see.

Well, nobody had any business in the women's dorm, including myself.
Well, sure enough, here he comes.
He comes up to me and looks around in the dark.
He strikes a match, and he sees me there.
You know, he was totally in shock.
What are you doing?
Just talking.
Oh, everything all right?
Yeah, everything's all right.
And he followed that.
So she was right.
He was going to make a pass.

It's been hard to get along with them.
So one day I said, what is the problem?
And he said, oh, you've been making passes at our dear customers.
And so I said, wait a minute.
Wait a minute.
That's not the way the story goes.
He said, we told you that.
Your husband told me.
I said, OK. Who told you?
Her husband told her.
I was doing things.
So I said, well, and I rattled on him.
Oh, she said, well, he's done that before.
Oh, I see.
I see.

The owner of Peddler Hill.
I see.
Right.

It was really a good scene if you could see that match.
The two of you lying on the lower bunk, whispering.
Well, you would have clothes on no matter what in this climate.
That's why there's such a small population up there.

The other time, the other one was the German Countess.

So I was in the room, and they were arguing outside the room whether he could come in.
So I know.

I was already inside.

I don't know.

not to press your advantage?

Yeah, selective.

Well, I was going to
I'm working up to getting as realistic as I can.
I really am.
I'm trying to... Because I know it's silly.
Of course, nowadays, I guess they're much more open about these things anyway.
Our code was, father told me, you can do it, but don't talk about it.
Don't talk about her to anybody about it.
That was our code.
I grew up with the same thing.
A gentleman does not discuss this thing.
Nor does the lady, actually.
We were struggling with this.
The lady wasn't involved in any of it.
Very good.
Very good.
You're a neck of the woods.
You were the lady if you were involved.
That's good.
Let me ask you, who was the first person that you remember helping you?
Was it Herb Lipkin, or was it Bill Klein, or was it Dennis Wilds, or was it... Who's the first person you remember...
helping you in some important way.
Migrant years,
I think that family that took me in, the Arkansas family, the Oklahoma family, took me in and they took me all the way to Oregon for that apple picking.
And I got that job, separate from them, I got that job on the ranch.
But I would have never gotten up there.
Winter of 45, maybe spring of 46.
They, I think they had a pickup truck or something, sleep in the back.
Transportation.
And you, your earnings go to the gas, you know, to throw in the pot full of food.
But to be taken in and not to be hassled, to have, you know, they know where, they knew where the jobs were.
I didn't.
where to go.
I mean, most of the time, nobody would know that these things, they're still existing today.
Ted Roth is still being traveled, I'm sure.
And they respected your privacy.
Yeah.
Did you know when you first met him that he'd also been a white reporter?
That was all screened out.
That was all screened out.
That's another skin that I shed.
You don't remember the name of that family, that first family?
Just Arkansas family.
Yeah, it was kind of an older man.
He had a tooth missing.
And that weathered look, you know, with the outdoor light, you know, and the cowboy hat and the woman.
Also that weathered look.
Tall folks, small folks?
A little bit.
He was fairly tall.
He was a little bit, I would say he was five foot six, eight.
I thought he was tall, almost six feet.
And she was probably five foot four.
And they were a very close family, you know.
They were always together, he and she.
They were more than ten feet apart.
And that was a good sight, you know, to see the basic social fabric of a family and be offered to be part of a family again, you know.
instead of being in the military camp, what have you.
Did they have children?
Yeah, they had some young boys, and then they had this daughter who was quite pretty, but she had a lot of acne at the time, unfortunately.
She was quite pretty otherwise.
She was probably 18, somewhere in there.
They always made little jokes about her and me, and she would get blush and run and hide the...
They, wherever we lived, whether it was a motel, a place that the farmers supply their migrant laborers.
Or labor camps.
Labor camps.
Oh, I see.
They supply a cabin to the families, you see, free.
Or, I don't know, charge my dad with the rent.
But they would compartment off little bedrooms.
These are one-room shacks usually, kitchen or sink of some kind.
And they'd hang blankets to make the rooms out of it for their daughters and for themselves.
I remember the time they joked about us, too.
You know, she got all red in the face.
threw up the blanket and disappeared into her little bedroom.
To fantasize, probably, about it being true.
Like I say, she had nice features.
Just going through the age of her acting, you understand.
Nice smile, very sweet.
Was there anything between you, any conversations, special talk?
It was more their jokes, which were just part of the unit.
Part of the unit, and I would just be very quiet and listen and say yes and thank you.
Keep my conversation down to a minimum.
They would try to draw me out and I would try to respond.
But, you know, because my vocabulary is so limited, you don't always have the pieces to tell a story.
You have a story, but there's one or two words missing, and there's no story.
You're just stuck.
You can't tell it.
Even not to this day.
Sometimes a word doesn't come that would fit into that story.
It makes you mad, you know, you just don't have it like that.
Vocabulary or just general?
I see.
Even to this day, I have to rearrange the story again to talk around it.
I do, too.
You do that?
Sure.
I can't think of the right word.
Yeah, I guess it's not that... Oh, I do it all the time.
I still don't think the picture of the mom and dad in this family, were they overweight, underweight?
He was very lean, lean body, and I think she was a little more stout.
But no real fat, no.
They worked too hard in the fields and in the trees.
They were both very tough, leathery, and I don't know whether strong people.
And the kids were really nice, lively boys.
and I was kind of, became the oldest boy almost in it, because I looked fairly young, always, no matter how old I was, I looked always four, five years younger than I was, you know.
So I was kind of an older brother to the boys, would play with them or be interested in what they were doing, which the parents weren't, you know.
So they gave me some kind of...
I found a place in the hierarchy of this family.
That's nice.
What kind of clothes did they wear?
Jeans, just torn jeans.
No, I think they wore dresses in those days.
I don't think they wore jeans.
And the print dresses, very much just...
Grapes of wrath, washed out, all torn, teeth missing, everybody had some kind of problem, probably because of the diet, not a balanced diet.
This was close enough to the war years so they may have asked you what you did during the war.
Never came up.
Never came up.
If you'd been in the war or sitting around the table talking about conversations when people said that they were in the
They had not.
He was too old, obviously.
His kids were too young.
Did you ever find yourself sitting in a bar where someone is telling stories about shooting up the Krauts in 1943?
Constantly.
Really?
And you've kept not a word about your opinion of when they mispronounce...
Rommel's name or they mispronounce Luftwaffe or Babel.
Surprisingly, very few of them really said anything bad other than, I mean bad that would affect me other than that they would say something.
But it wasn't nearly as bad as the newspapers.
The newspapers were hard to read because of all the border stories, day after day.
It was hard to read.
Who wants to be part of that?
Certainly, certainly.
Running with the migrant workers,
Did you ever find yourself badly treated?
Were you robbed, or beaten, or badly treated, or had your shoes stolen, or things that would happen on a migrant life?
Very much in those days.
They had made it through the war.
Some of them might have gone and made a little money in the defense plans, maybe.
When they started closing down, they probably had to go back to their regular lives.
So I get the picture of you during those days as being a loner, being very quiet, keeping to yourself, attaching yourself from one group to another, family if possible.
Because I liked the human contact.
Yes.
You know, I mean, it was fun to...
to sit there in this room before or after dinner and have boys playing and yakking away, you know, the older people talking to themselves and have something going on.
What have I given up?
What have I lost?
Pretty, yeah, pretty, a lot of grief.

having lost my family and my home town and the whole clinic was very very hard to overcome and that's why I try to read all these books to make sure that my head stays straight on and that I you know there must be some other there must be some way of
getting over this, this cannot, you know, go on forever to, to weep over your family, the loss of your family, the loss of your, everything you've ever known and had, you know.
So it, it, you, then you read stories that had happened to other people, not just me,
Not just the Germans.
It happened to other nationalities.
And it just got better.
Of course, as time went on, it went all over the world.
It never stopped.
Somebody has the same problem as I have.

looking for a port, searching out a ship, finding yourself with this family.

String the days, the good days together.

That was when I taught tennis there and briefly worked for that department store.
And I was, they were terrifying me, those stores with the bells, and I just felt inadequate in my job.
I did not feel that I could really function or do what I was doing.
These other things were just interfering.
Everything was driving me crazy in these places.
I mean, they're lovely places, these stores, but I couldn't relax.
I was nervous as a cat.
You never had any response to World War II movies, the Holocaust series on television, or the movie The Desert Fox.
I remember with James Mason.
I may have seen parts of it.
But you didn't gravitate toward those movies to see how they were portraying what you did or that you were doing.
You stayed away from them for particular reasons?
No, I didn't want to go backwards on those.
I really got into this self-healing process.
And if you want to heal yourself, you cannot go back to scratch your scab, your wound, constantly.
It won't heal.
And I try to do this with the kids when they get in, raising kids.
Get them going on the positive and string the good days together.
Don't louse it up with bad vibes.
If you can help it, you're going to get them.
You're going to get your bad vibes whether you want to or not.
